### Slide 5: Market Size

**Purpose:** Show the business opportunity

**Framework:** TAM â†’ SAM â†’ SOM

**What to Include:**
- Total Addressable Market (TAM)
- Serviceable Available Market (SAM)
- Serviceable Obtainable Market (SOM)
- Growth trajectory
- Market trends supporting your timing

**Structure:**

```
Market Opportunity

TAM (Total Addressable Market):
$XXX million - [Entire market size]
[How calculated]

SAM (Serviceable Available Market):
$XX million - [Realistic market you can serve]
[How calculated]

SOM (Serviceable Obtainable Market):
$X million - [What you can capture in 3-5 years]
[How calculated]

Why Now:
[Market trend or shift creating opportunity]
```

**Example - Good:**

```
$2.3M Market Opportunity at Georgian Universities

TAM: $12.5M
â€¢ 160,000 university students in Georgia
â€¢ $78/student/year average spend on edu software
â€¢ 160,000 Ã— $78 = $12.5M

SAM: $4.2M
â€¢ 54,000 students at Tbilisi & Kutaisi universities
â€¢ 54,000 Ã— $78 = $4.2M

SOM: $2.3M (by Year 3)
â€¢ Target: 30,000 students (55% of SAM)
â€¢ 30,000 Ã— $78 = $2.3M

Why Now:
Georgian universities digitizing post-COVID â†’ 
perfect timing for unified student platform
```

**Example - Bad:**

```
Market Size

The education market is worth billions.

There are millions of students.

We will capture 1% which is still a lot.
```

**Why Bad Example Fails:**
- No specific numbers
- No calculation methodology
- Too broad (global vs. your market)
- No realistic path to market share

**Calculation Methods:**

**Top-Down (Start with big number):**
```
Market reports â†’ 
Filter to your segment â†’ 
Calculate your addressable portion
```

**Bottom-Up (Start with customer):**
```
Average revenue per customer Ã— 
Number of reachable customers = 
Total market opportunity
```

**Your Market Size Checklist:**
- [ ] TAM, SAM, SOM all calculated
- [ ] Methodology explained
- [ ] Numbers are realistic
- [ ] Growth trajectory shown
- [ ] Timing/trends explained

