## Design Principles

### Visual Design Guidelines

**Typography:**

```
âœ… DO:
â€¢ Use 30pt minimum font size
â€¢ Max 5 bullets per slide
â€¢ Max 7 words per bullet
â€¢ Sans-serif fonts (cleaner)

âŒ DON'T:
â€¢ Paragraphs of text
â€¢ Multiple font types
â€¢ Tiny footnotes
â€¢ Cluttered slides
```

**Color Palette:**

```
âœ… DO:
â€¢ 2-3 colors maximum
â€¢ High contrast (dark text on light bg)
â€¢ Consistent throughout deck
â€¢ Professional, not garish

âŒ DON'T:
â€¢ Rainbow colors
â€¢ Neon or hard-to-read colors
â€¢ Different color schemes per slide
â€¢ Low contrast combinations
```

**Images & Graphics:**

```
âœ… DO:
â€¢ High resolution (no pixelation)
â€¢ Relevant and purposeful
â€¢ Consistent style
â€¢ Proper attribution if needed

âŒ DON'T:
â€¢ Cheesy stock photos
â€¢ Clip art
â€¢ Stretched or distorted images
â€¢ Too many images per slide
```

**Data Visualization:**

```
âœ… DO:
â€¢ Simple, clear charts
â€¢ Labeled axes
â€¢ Highlighted key insight
â€¢ One chart per slide

âŒ DON'T:
â€¢ 3D pie charts
â€¢ Multiple complex charts
â€¢ Unlabeled data
â€¢ Excel default colors
```

### Layout Best Practices

**Slide Layouts:**

```
Title Slide:
â€¢ Center-aligned
â€¢ Large, clear title
â€¢ Minimal text

Content Slides:
â€¢ Consistent header placement
â€¢ Generous white space
â€¢ Left-aligned text (easier to read)
â€¢ Visual hierarchy (size, color, position)

Visual Slides:
â€¢ Large, impactful image/chart
â€¢ Minimal text overlay
â€¢ Clear takeaway message
```

**The Squint Test:**

Stand back 10 feet from your screen. Squint your eyes. Can you still read the slide and get the main point?

âœ… If yes: Good design  
âŒ If no: Too much text, refine

